Report for Simulation Video #3

In this report we answer the same question reviewed in Radiant Tutorial Series: Probability Calculator Video 2. To review, lets first see how to solve the question about Brita’s water filters using Basics > Probability calculator.

  1. Since the distribution over the number of gallons before the filter signals replacement is normally distributed and governed by the historical mean and standard deviation, I selected “Normal” as the distribution type in the probability calculator. The mean is 100 and the standard deviation is 8.

\(\pm\) 10 gallons from the mean indicates that the lower bound is 90 and the upper bound is 110. Thus the probability that a filter’s signal occurs \(\pm\) 10 gallons from the mean is 0.789.

result <- prob_norm(mean = 100, stdev = 8, lb = 90, ub = 110)
summary(result)
Probability calculator
Distribution: Normal
Mean        : 100 
St. dev     : 8 
Lower bound : 90 
Upper bound : 110 

P(X < 90) = 0.106
P(X > 90) = 0.894
P(X < 110) = 0.894
P(X > 110) = 0.106
P(90 < X < 110)     = 0.789
1 - P(90 < X < 110) = 0.211
plot(result)

  1. The relenvant distribution here is the Binomial. From question (a) we know that the probability of a filter with good quality is 0.789 so I selected “Binomial” as distribution type in the probability calculator with \(n = 5\) and \(p = 0.789\). I set the lower bound as 3 and the probability that at least 3 of 5 examined filters are good is 0.933.
result <- prob_binom(n = 5, p = 0.789, lb = 3)
summary(result)
Probability calculator
Distribution: Binomial
n           : 5 
p           : 0.789 
Mean        : 3.945 
St. dev     : 0.912 
Lower bound : 3 
Upper bound :  

P(X  = 3) = 0.219
P(X  < 3) = 0.067
P(X <= 3) = 0.285
P(X  > 3) = 0.714
P(X >= 3) = 0.933
plot(result)

We will now solve the same questions using the simulation tool in Radiant. I chose Normal distribution in the Model > Simulate tab. For the normal distribution, lets choose the variable name “brita” with mean of 100 gallons and standard deviation of 8 gallons. I specified the simulation formula as \(good\_quality = (brita > 90)\ \&\ (brita < 110)\). I set the random seed to 1234 and ran 5,000 simulations. The simulated data was saved in the dataset simdat.

The simulation summary below shows that the probability that a filter’s signal occurs ±10 gallons from the mean is 0.7916. This is very close to the theoretical value that we derived from the distribution above and in Probability Calculator Video #2 (i.e. 0.789). By increasing the number of simulation runs, e.g., to 500,000, we would get even closer to the theoretical estimate.

simdat <- simulater(
  norm = "brita 100 8", 
  form = "good_quality = (brita > 90) & (brita < 110)", 
  seed = 1234, 
  nr = 5000
)
summary(simdat, dec = 4)

plot(simdat, custom = FALSE)

register("simdat")

In part (b) we want to determine the probability of finding 3 or more “good quality” filters out of a sample of 5. This means we should repeat the initial simulation from part (a) above, 5 times. To do this I selected “brita” as the variable to re-simulate in the Repeat tab, and selected the variable of interest “good_quality” in the Output variable box. In this example, I would like to determine the number of filters with good quality across 5 repetitions, so I selected Simulation in the Group by box and sum in the Apply function box. The result shows that the probability that at least 3 of 5 examined filters are good quality is 0.9348, which is also very similar to what I got above and in the second video of probability calculator (i.e., 0.933). By increasing the number of simulation runs, e.g., to 500,000, we could get even closer to the theoretical estimate.

repdat <- repeater(
  simdat, 
  nr = 5, 
  vars = "brita", 
  sum_vars = "good_quality", 
  form = "good_quality_3 = good_quality_sum >= 3", 
  seed = 1234
)
summary(repdat, dec = 4)

register("repdat")

To better understand the data generated in the repeated simulation set “Apply function” to None by removing all shown functions (i.e., click on the x). Also remove the formula or put a # in front of the formula so it will not be evaluated. Run the repeated simulation again and save the data as repdat1. In Data > View you will see there are 25,000 entries in this dataset (i.e., 5 repetitions of a simulation with 5,000 runs). I am going to reshape it into a \(5,000 \times 5\) matrix in the Data > Transform tab by selecting “Spread column” as Transformation type. Select “.rep” as the key and “good_quality” as the value. In the first row of the reshaped dataset we can see that the first two filters are good quality. In the second row all 5 filters are good.

repdat1 <- repeater(
  simdat, 
  nr = 5, 
  vars = "brita", 
  sum_vars = "good_quality", 
  seed = 1234, 
  fun = "none"
)
summary(repdat1, dec = 3)

register("repdat1")
## Spread columns
repdat1_spread <- spread(repdat1, .rep, good_quality)
## register the new dataset
register("repdat1_spread", "repdat1")
## filter and sort the dataset
dtab(repdat1_spread, dec = 2, nr = 10) %>% render()

Now lets take another look at the repdat dataset we created earlier. You can see in the first row that the sum of good_quality, i.e., good_quality_sum created through repeated simulation is also equal to 2. In the second row we see that good_quality_sum is equal to 5, just as we see in the reshaped matrix above.

## filter and sort the dataset
dtab(repdat, dec = 2, nr = 10) %>% render()

Finally, let’s take another look at the dataset (repdat) in the Data > View tab. If I filter data by the criterion \(good\_quality >= 3\), 4,674 entries will be selected, which is the same number I got for good_quality_3 in the repeated simulation shown above.
